{"/service/ndnp/wyu/batch_wyu_afton_ver01/data/sn92066926/00340588083/1921011901/0934.xml":{"full_text":"TWO\nNorthern Wyoming Herald\nOFFICIAL PAPER OF PARK COUNTY AND CITY OF CODY\nNEWTON AND SHAW, Publishers\n_____________________________________________________ j\nEntered as Second Class matter October 27, 1910, at the Postoffice at Cody,;,\nWyoming, under the Act of Congress of March 3, 1879.\nI Foreign Advertising Representative\n1 THE AMERICAN PRESS ASSOCIATION\nr. -rr r r -'LI\". i- n n \u2014^nojvvw.nnrjwiruxnjuwiruwinj-rm.fLn.wjn. .n.-,.-inrL-innjwici*- I\nSubscription Rates, per year $2.00\nSubscription Rates, six months 1.00\nAdvertising Rates, display space, per single column inch .25\nline Readers, per line., .10\nPROSPERITY AHEAD\nThere is much comfort to be had\nform the statement recently of Judge\nElbert H. Gary, head of the United j\nStates Steel corporation, the greatest\nbusiness concern the world has ever!\nproduced.\nJudge Gary says a long period of\nprosperity is just ahead of the people j\nof the United States.\nWhen Judge Gary opens his mouth 1\nhe is in the habit of saying something,\nand he never says a thing unless he\nknows what he is talking about.\nHe has been a wise prophet in the i\npast because he possesses the ability:\nto read conditions and possibilities\nas they are.\nThere is no reason why this pro-!\nphesy should not be one of wisdom in\nthis case, because there is no reason'\nwhy we should not prosper and every;\nreason why we should.\nBanks and financiers generally\nstate that we have passed through our\nworst period of depression and are\nnow on the up grade. Only the rank-\nest kind of pessimism can hold us back,\neat kind of pessimism can hod us back.\nAnd who wants to be a pessimist\nwhen every human instinct spurs us\non to optimism.\nLet\u2019s demonstrate our faith in the j\nreturn of prosperity by recognizing;\nthe fact that it is here and by doing\nour share toward its maintenance in\nthis community.\nLet the watchword be production, l\nwisdom in spending, and the employ- j\nment of a systematic course of saving.;\nA proportionate amount of the pros\nperity of the country belongs to the i\npeople of this community.\nLet\u2019s get all we can and keep all we\nget.\nOther communities will be doing\nHie same.\nDOLLARS AND TITLES\nAn American widow of wealth has\nfollowed the nauseating example of\nmany others and has married a for\neign title\u2014this time a Greek prince.\nShe is reaping the bitter experience\nof others by being royally snubbed in\nAthens while the prince is presumably\nenjoying the money with which she\npurchased him.\nSome day we will have a law for\nbidding the the incomes of such for- j\ntunes being taken from the country,!\nother than a bare sufficiency for a\nperson\u2019s comfortable support.\nBut in the meantime self respecting\nAmericans will continue to be humil- j\niated by reading of such spectacles as\nthe one that has just been.enacted in\nAthens.\nA woman who is not worth marry\ning for love is not worth having at\nany price, and no self respecting man\never marries a woman for her money.\nBut empty heads and empty pockets j\n\u2014pooh.\nNOT NEEDED HERE\nIt has been frequently said that\nold dogs cu.i i.ot b.i laugh*, new tricks*\nbut a Chicago r..-v/spipr*r* apparently\nthinks otherwise.\nA reporter for the paper spends\neach day in traveling about the city,\naccosting all sorts of people and test\ning their politeness. He finds means\nof coming in contact with the clerks\nin the stores, business men in their\noffices, public officials on duty, judg\nes, ministers, housewives and the pub\nlic generally.\nSometimes he is dressed in fine\nrainment, and at others he is in rags,\nbut always he is unknown.\nTo the person making the most j\ncourteous reply to his inquires he pre\nsents a check entitling the person to\nfifty dollars. The check is paid by\nthe paper and the polite one gets a\nwriteup in its columns.\nIts effect has become marked, even!\nin a city the size of Chicago.\nDoes any one in this town want to\ncotribute SSO a day to a campaign\nof courtesy?\nIf so, come across. This paper will\nfurnish the publicity.\nBut, then, perhaps it is not needed\nhere.\nWhat think you.\nCOAL AT $4.50\nThe navy department was able to\nbuy coal at less than $4.50 per ton at\na time when the general public was\npaying more than three times that\nfigure, and while the Department of j\nJustice was apparently unable to find j\nanything materially wrong with the i\nfuel Bituataion The Wilson adminis\ntration has never let its right hand\nknow what its left hand was doing.\nPresident Wilson has again sent the\nti*vne of John Skelton Williams to a\nSenate he knows will refuse to con\nfinn. John Skelton is about as well\nqualified to fill the office of control\nler of the Currency as a Missouri mule\nwould be to sing Caruso\u2019s roles in\ngrand opera.\u2014Dubuque Times-Joum\nml.\nThe need of the hour is to get busy\nand stay busy.\ni\nMICKIE SAYS\n3\nX OLE CM> GRASS \u00a9AMQ 1 \"'N\nwsR. ac\u00dfi wewbwsf -cvf wpcrs,) i\nOVKO euaSl NEARS UCT9O AVi' J\nUsfe MET TC> UCAR OF- AC6SE\nCnWWCUE A httDWSBARER. WJZ.\n\u2019carried cwt reef farsv oecuz.]\nSavee>je& p*rt\u00dfov\\ 'jowuowaOf' t\n(uva A'DVERtfS'VAS ER. <3tOFRED I\n\u2014.uyg, parsrA\n'tirtXX jgfe t\u00dfh TCc-pittcm*\u2019 ii\n0 p|p ftogferPrittW I\n\ni=-\nWILLIAM R. COE OF\nPARK COUNT GIVES\n$15,000 TO HOSPITAL\n(Cheyenne Tribune)\nLast summer William S. Coe, of\nPark county, Wyominb, while in Chey\nenne became very much interested in\nthe Memorial Hospital of Laramie\ncounty being erected in honor of Fran\nces Warren Pershing. Mr. Coe is iden\ntified with large business interests in\nNew York, but owns a ranch in Park\ncounty and is enthusiastic over the\ndevelopment of Wyoming He con-,\nferred with various members of the\nboard of trustees of the hospital and\nwith Bishop Thomas as to its scope\nand management when completed\nBeing satisfied at that time he later\nmade a subscription of $5,000.\nLearning that the hospital was go\ning to cost a great deal more than or\niginally cantemplated, Mr. Coe made\nfurther inquiries as to its progress\nand needs with the result indicated\nin the following telegram:\nNew York N. Y., January 13. Bish\nop N. S. Thomas, Cheyenne Wyoming\n\u2014Your letter of the 10th received,\ni i Judge Lacey\u2019s letter has convinced\nme of the worthiness of the Memorial\nHospital of Laramie county ,and you\ncan increase my subscription to a\ntotal of $15,000. The additional\nSIO,OOO will be paid during the year\nas per my letter of December 29th.\n\u201cI trust there will be a liberal and\nsufficient response from fro Cheyenne\nand Laramie county people to com\nplete and properly equip the hospital.\n\u2014W. R. Coe.\nWithin a few days the board will\ni send out notices calling for the second\ni installments of the subscriptions made\nlast June. It is hoped that payments\nwill be promptly made and that new\nsubscriptions will be forthcoming.\nBUY YOUR\n\nBUILDING LOAN\nSTOCK\nfrom the\nCody\nBuilding Loan\nAssociation\nA HOME CONCERN\nfor\nHOME PEOPLE\nj\nMoney to Loan on Cody\nProperty\nI\nD. A. TINKCOM, Pres.\nERNEST J. GOPPERT, Sec.\nSI,OOO Reward\ni\nwill be paid for information leading U\nthe arrest and conviction of any per\nson or persons stealing stock belong\ntng to\nW. R. COE\ni\nCody, Wyo.\nNORTHERN WYOMING HERALD\nThe hospital is now being erected\nand from time to time it is necessary i\nto make payments to the contractors.\nMr Coe has made geatrous gifts to\nCody and gave the state the Pennewill 1\ncollection of world-was trophies.\n\nSHERIDAN TOWN BOARD 1\nGOES THE LIMIT IN 1\nCLEANUP CAMPAIGN 1\nA new city ordinance that may j\ncause consternation in some quarters\norgan its process of enactment Mon\nday when an ordinance, sponsored by\nthe mayor, was introduced, making it\nillegal to maintain any card table, or\npossi ss any chips or cards in any\nroom connected with or capable of be\ning entered from any soft drink par\nlor, cigar store or other building\nwhere public business is transacted.\nFor violation of the ordinance a fine\nof SIOO may be assessed.\nThe ordinance also provides that\nthe gambling tables may be seized by\nany police officer, taken before the po-\nlice judge and upon proper showing\nbeing made they may be destroyed.\nAnother or- :,lance introduced pro\nvides that all screens must be re\nmoved from the windows of soft drink\nparlors and provide? also that the\nproprietors must so arrange the\nbuilding that the view of all parts\nof the interior from the streets must\nIbe unobstructed. Several penalties\nare provided for the violation of the\nordinance.\nROAD PATROL SYSTEM\nPUT INTO OPERATION\nBIG HORN COUNTY\nAt their meeting on Tuesday the\nj county commissioner? organized by\nelecting Mr. John Weintz as chair\ni man for the coming two year*,\nj The commissioners announce that\nthey have adopted a plan lor road\nwork which they hope will work out\nto better advantage than the* meth\nods of the past. Under this plan two\nmen will be employed in each of the\nthree districts\u2014the north, central\nand southern districts. These men\nwill be responsible to the commis-\nsioner having charge of that partic-1\nCONFIDENCE\nWe very much appreciate the confidence many of our customers have in us.\nOne customer the other day stated v he felt whatever our price was .that he was j.\ngetting value. Cash\" sales enable] any business concern to reduce ex\npenses, any one will and can sell for less if they do not have book accounts and\nthe loss incidental thereto.\nThere is a great difference in merchandise of all kinds. Wedetermined to handle good grades. .Take a piece of cloth\nfor instance and examine it under a microscope. You will see an intricate net work of crossing fine threads and under\nthe microscope you can observe tiny air spaces. The closer woven the better the doth. We will be glad to show our\ncustomers the difference between many cheap calicos, ginghams and percales offered by some mail order houses. We\nwill show you that where there is a difference in price, there is a difference in quality. For instance onr percale has\neighty eight threads per square inch, and samples we have from Montgomery Ward Company have sixty-six threads\nto the square inch. We invite you to come in and see this.\nOur prices are on present wholesale market\nBest Quality C. P. S. Gingham, 27 inches wide, was\n45c, now 22c\nBest Quality Toile Du Norde, 27 inches wide, was\n50c, now 27%c\nBest Quality Ideal Percale, 36 inches wide, was 45c\nnow 20c\nWOOL GOODS\nAll wool navy blue serge steamed and shrunk, 50\ninches wide, was $3.75, now $2.55\nAll wool Black Storm Serge, steamed and shrunk,\n50 inches wide, was $3.75, now $2.55\nAll Wool French Serge, 42 inches wide was $3.50,\nnow $2.40\nAll Wool Navy Blue French Serge, 42 inches wide,\nwas $3.50, now $2.40\nAll Wool Dark Brown French Serge, 42 inches\nwide, was $3.50, now $2.40\nOne Lot of Mina Taylor Dresses at one-half price.\nOne Lot of Mina Taylor Dresses at one-fourth price.\nBig Reductions in Fleischer-Young Knitting Worsted, Floss and\nSaxony in All the Popular Shades.\nLadies tailor-made Globe union suits, cotton, was\n$3.00, now $2.35\nLadies tailor-made Globe union suits, wool, was\n$5.16, now $3.75\nLadies tailor-made, Globe union suits, silk and\nwool, was $6.75, now $4.85\nChildren\u2019s tailor-made, Globe union suits, cotton\nwas $2.00, now 1 $1.55\nCost mm* Ca\nwhereitpakstoiwTcash\n\nular district and work will be done\nunder instructions of that commission\ner.\nThese men with their teams will\nbe kept at work throughout the year,\n'or as much of the year as it is found\nto be feasable to do so. The best of\nmen will be secured\u2014men who know\nhow to do the work and who will\nfaithfully attend to the business as- j\nsigned. They will be prepared to\nstay on the job night and day, stop\nping for the night wherever their\nwork is dropped for the day, and go\ning ahead in the morning without\nout the loss of time necessary to get\nback and forth from work.\nWith this sort of a plan, which will\ntake care to a certain extent of main\ntenance of country roads, it ii hoped\nthat Big Horn county will have better\nroads than ever before at less ex\npense.\u2014Big Horn Rustler.\nIf we could see ourselves as others\nsee us, most of us would prefer to\nlook at something else.\nHealth Restored\n\u201cMy horse was in such run down\ncondition I thought he would die.\nAfter feeding him Dr. LeGear\u2019s Stock\nl Powders, he is as well as ever and is\n1 now as good looking a horse as there\nis in this section.\u201d\u2014J. C. Huste, Rock\nbridge, Baths, Va.\nDr. LeGear\u2019s Stock Powders build\nup the body vitality and muscular\nenergy of your horses and mules, in\nsure more meat with less feed from\nyour hogs, sheep and cattle and help\nyour cows produce more and richer\nmilk.\nMr. Huste\u2019s small expenditure\nsaved him the price of a horse. Dr.\nLeGear can also help you. For 28\nyears as a Veterinary SuTgeon and\nexpert poultry breeder, he has de\nvoted himself to the compounding of\nremedies for ailments of stock and\nj poultry. Whenever you have an ail\nment among your stock or poultry get\nthe proper Dr. LeGear Remedy from\nyour dealer. It must satisfy you, or\nI your money will be refunded.\nTo the Dyspeptic\nWould you not like to feel that\nyour stomach troubles are over, that\nyou can eat any kind of food that you\ncrave? .Consider then the fact that\ni\nThis is the right season of the year\nto get your harness and other\nleather goods oiled. The added\nwearing qualities make the ex\npense as nothing.\nEd. BOHLIN\nv\nWhen Snow and Slush\nare quite the fashion in the North, balmy breezes, annny\nskies, moonlit bays and tropical flowers are the fashion in\nthe South, and those who have gone there are enjoying nil\nsorts of out-door recreation\u2014luxuritaing in the exotk at\nmospheremosphere, unmindful of furnace fires, heavy\nwraps and the constant menace of catching cold. Those\nwho bid farewell to the north at this time, return realizing\nmore than ever before the real value of a winter vacation\nin that romantic, historic and beautiful alnd south of the\nMason and Dixon line.\ntSart right! Take a Burlington-planned-trip\u2014past inter\nesting and eereblrated places. Go one way and return\nanother. As soon as you decide the date on which you\nwish to leave, let me know, because travel is heavy down\nthat way and I want to protect your comfort and pleasure\nby reserving proper sleeping car space in advance.\n\u201cI T. F. KLING,\nTicket Agent.\nBest Quality Sea Side Percale, 36 inches wide, was\n55c, now 271/fec\nCalicos, best American print, 27 inches wide, was\n25c, now 1714 c\nOuting Flannel, (half century grade), was 35c\nnow 25c\nAll Wool, Black Broadcloth, 52 Inches wide, was\n$4.00, now $2.65\nGood Grade Poplin, 36 inches wide, red, green,\nblue and black, was $2.50, now $1.70\nRed Middy Flannel, 27 inches wide, was, $2.75\nnow $2.00\nFine Quality White Serge, 38 inches wide SI.OO\nAll wool white Suiting, 45 inches wide $2.15\nChildren\u2019s tailor made Globe union suits, wool,\nwas $3.75, now $2.85\nChildren\u2019s tailor made Globe union suits, wool,\nwas $4.60, now S3XS\nChildren\u2019s wool sweaters, were SB.OO, $4.00 and\n$5.00. Now your choice SIXO\nLadies voile and organdie waists were S2XO, SB.OO\nand $3.50. Now your choice SIXB\nWEDNESDAY, JANUARY 19, 1921\nChamberlain\u2019s tablets have cured oth\ners\u2014why not you. There are many\nwho have been restored to health by\ntaking these tablets and can now eat.\nany kind of food that they crave.","height":"22324","width":"15420"}}
